[2]
Date: 25 Apr 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Australian Broadcasting Corp., 22 Apr 2005 [edited]
<http://www.abc.net.au/rural/content/2005/s1351462.htm>

Fruit still moving out of quarantine area
-------------------------------------------
Domestic trade of fruit is still possible out of the quarantined
citrus-growing area in central Queensland, despite confirmation of a 5th
case of CC yesterday [21 Apr 2005]. The National Management Group ordered
the destruction of the remaining 70 000 trees on the 2PH Selma Road property.
But Chris Adriaansen from Queensland Biosecurity, says a resumption to
domestic trade will still be recommended next week [final week April 2005].
He said there's a difference between the infected properties and those 5
other properties within the PQA that have no evident CC infection. A pest
risk analysis indicated that any risk associated with the movement of fruit
from those 5 non-infected properties is completely within acceptable limits
and can be mitigated through inspection treatment and certification.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
