[3]
Date: 25 Apr 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Australian Broadcasting Corp., 21 Apr 2005 [edited]
<http://www.abc.net.au/rural/content/2005/s1350535.htm>

New citrus canker outbreak reported
-----------------------------------------
A 5th CC outbreak has been detected on 2PH farms in central Queensland,
according to owner John Pressler. "It's a scattered area, which would
encompass several acres, as have the previous ones, over a kilometer in any
direction from the previous ones," he said. According to Pressler, it would
appear that this is the 3rd finding that can be traced back to the rain
events of January and February 2005, and it has obviously been brought in
by wind during that period.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Destruction of the remaining CC-infected citrus trees on IP2 is the only
appropriate management option. The evidence certainly suggests that heavy
winds in January and February 2005 were a major factor contributing to
dissemination of the bacterium (_Xanthomonas_ _axonopodis_ pv. _citri_) to
trees on the affected properties. The loss of nearly 600 000 CC-infected
trees dramatically illustrates the capability of the bacterium to wage
destruction on a massive scale. - Mod.DH]
